With the aim of evaluating the selectivity performance, the interfering aromatic carboxylic acids (m-PA, o-PA), amino acids (arginine, Glutathione, glutamine, tryptophan), glucose, Dopamine(DA), Adrenaline(AD) and common biorelevant ions (Zn2+, Cd2+, Cl−, SO4
                     2−) were investigated by the similar method. Their fluorescent signal responses and the corresponding luminescence variations were negligible compared to the presence of DPA (Fig. 7
                     ). These results supported that the CQDs-EDTA-Eu probe is selective for efficient recognition of DPA in aqueous solution. In this way, this hybrid sensor exhibits great potentials in the recognition of the anthrax biomarker.

Glutathione plays a critical role within cells and its deficiency leads to the disease progressions. The sensing ability of GSH based on CQDs-EDTA-Eu-DPA/Cu (10μg/ml CQDs-EDTA-Eu, 10μM DPA, 100μM Cu2+) has been performed. GSH was prepared in distilled water and added in portions. Samples were excited at 282nm and emission spectra were collected. Unexpectedly, the red luminescence has been significantly enhanced. (Fig. 9
                     ) The emission intensity change versus the concentration of GSH follows the simple linear equation y=3.97 x − 23.1 (R2
                     =0.9937). The linear range is from 0 to 50μM (Fig. S8). The detection of limit (DL) was determined to be 50nM.
